Networks¶

Networks, An Introduction, M.E.J. Newman, Oxford University Press, 2010¶

Why Networks?¶

There are many systems of interest to scientist that are composed of individual parts or components linked together in some way.

One of the most important aspects of systems is the interactive behavior of the system (sometimes neglected), which is the pattern of connections between components.

The idea is that the pattern of connectiosn in a given system can be represented as a network.

So, what is a network?¶

In its simple form, a collection of points joined together in pairs by lines.

  • Points are referred to as vertices or nodes
  • Lines are referred to as edges.

Visualization¶

A first step in analyzing the structure of a network is often to make a picture of it.

Visualization can be an extraordinary useful tool in the analysis of network data.

The Visualization Problem¶

Direct visualization of networks is only really usefull for networks up to a hundred or thousands vertices.

Many of the networks that scientist are interested us today have thousands or even millions of vertices, which means that that visualziation is not of much help.

Understanding the network structure¶

Unless we know something about the structure of these networks, we can not hope to understand fully how the corresponding systems work.

Properties of Networks¶

In response to this need, network theory (or graph theory) has developed a large toolset of measures and metrics that can help us understand what our network data are telling us, even in cases where visualziation is impossible.

At the core our aim is to answer the following questions:

  • What is the form and function of the system the network represents?
  • What properties of networked systems can we measure? With which particular method?
  • How are those properties related to the practial issue we care about?

Structural Analysis¶

The inquiry for understanding the network by its properties and measures is called Structural Analysis.

Primarilly is concerned with:

  • Centrality (nodes or edges)
  • Hubs (vertices with unusually high degree)
  • Community detection or clustering

Path¶

A Path is a series of nodes that can be traversed following edges between them.
The length of the path is the number of edges in it.

Paths are used to determine connectedness
Two nodes in a graph are called connected if there is a path between them in the network.

We are interested in the shortest path, that is called the geodesic distance between node 0 and 6 for example.

In [16]:
print("The path from node 0 to node 6 is", nx.shortest_path(G,source=0,target=6))

nx.draw(G, node_color='c',edge_color='k', with_labels=True)

The path from node 0 to node 6 is [0, 1, 4, 6]

A bridge is an edge that connects two otherwise separate group of nodes in the networks. A node is a cutpoint if its removal will disconect the graph. Hubs are refer to the most connected nodes in the network.

Centrality¶

Centrality measures how central a node is in the network

Degree Centrality¶

Undirected- unweighted graphs¶

Number of edges it has.
Is a good measure of the total connection a node has, but will not necessarily indicate the importance of a node in connecting others or how central it is to the main group.

The degree centrality values are normalized by dividing by the maximum possible degree in a simple graph n-1 where n is the number of nodes in G.

$$\frac{degree_i}{n-1}$$

In [18]:
nodes=[("a"), ("b"),("g"), ("j"), ("p")]

    print("The node", i, "degree is", nx.degree(c)[i], "and its degree centrality is", nx.degree_centrality(c)[i])

nx.draw(c, node_color='c',edge_color='k', with_labels=True)

The node b degree is 4 and its degree centrality is 0.25
The node g degree is 1 and its degree centrality is 0.0625
The node j degree is 2 and its degree centrality is 0.125
The node p degree is 8 and its degree centrality is 0.5

Closeness centrality¶

How close a node is to all other nodes.

It is calculated as the average of the shortest path length from the node to every other node in the network.
Indicates nodes as more central if they are closer to the most nodes in the graph, i.e., visual centrality.

You can also see Closness centrality as the cost of spread (info) to al other nodes.

Closeness centrality of a node u is the reciprocal of the sum of the shortest path distances from u to all n-1 other nodes.
Since the sum of distances depends on the number of nodes in the graph, closeness is normalized by the sum of minimum possible distances n-1.

$$C(u) = \frac{n - 1}{\sum_{v=1}^{n-1} d(v, u)}$$

where d(v, u) is the shortest-path distance between v and u, and n is the number of nodes in the graph.

Betweenes centrality¶

How important a node is to the shortest paths through the network.
We select a pair of nodes and find all the shortest paths between those nodes . Then we compute the fraction of those shortest paths that include node N.

It captures how important a node is in the flow of information from one part of the network to another

Betweenness centrality of a node v is the sum of the fraction of all-pairs shortest paths that pass through v:

$$c_B(v) =\sum_{s,t \in V} \frac{\sigma(s, t|v)}{\sigma(s, t)}$$

where $V$ is the set of nodes, $\sigma(s, t)$ is the number of shortest $(s, t)$-paths, and $\sigma(s, t|v)$ is the number of those paths passing through some node $v$ other than $s, t$. If $s = t$, $\sigma(s, t) = 1$, and if $v$ $\in {s, t}$, $\sigma(s, t|v) = 0$.

Eigenvector centrality¶

Measures a node's importance while giving consideration to the importance of its neighbors. To determinice a node's influence in the network, it performs a matrix calculation to determine what is called the principal eigenvector using the adjacency matrix.

Eigenvector centrality computes the centrality for a node based on the centrality of its neighbors. The eigenvector centrality for node $i$ is

$\mathbf{Ax} = \lambda \mathbf{x}$

where $A$ is the adjacency matrix of the graph $G$ with eigenvalue $\lambda$. By virtue of the PerronFrobenius theorem, there is a unique and positive solution if &\lambda& is the largest eigenvalue associated with the eigenvector of the adjacency matrix $A$.

Density¶

The number of edges in the graph divided by the number of possible edges.

The density for undirected graphs is

$d = \frac{2m}{n(n-1)},$

and for directed graphs is

$d = \frac{m}{n(n-1)},$

where $n$ is the number of nodes and $m$ is the number of edges in $G$.

Connectivity¶

Measures how edges are distributed.

Is a count of the minium number of nodes that would have to be removed before the graph becomes disconnected.

This implementation is based on Kanevskys algorithm for finding all minimum-size node cut-sets of an undirected graph $G$; ie the set (or sets) of nodes of cardinality equal to the node connectivity of $G$. Thus if removed, would break $G$ into two or more connected components.

In [33]:
print(nx.node_connectivity(c))
cutsets = list(nx.all_node_cuts(c))
cutsets

1

The Empiral Study of Social Networks¶

One of the "Founding fathers" Jacob Moreno, a Romanian immigrant to America who in 1930s became interested in the dynamics of social interaction within groups of people.

In 1934, he published "Who Shall Survive? A new Approach to the Problem of Human Interrelations.", which contained the seeds of the field of sociometry, which later bacame social network analysis.

What are Social Networks?¶

A social network is a structure composed of a set of actors, some of whose members are connected by a set of one or more relations.

Is a description of a social structure between actors (individuals or organizations). It indicates the ways in which they are connected (interact) though various social familiarities.

To probe different type different types of social interactions could be represented by different kinds of social networks addressed by different kind of questions.

Underlying Assumptions¶

The network perspective emphasizes structural relations as its key oriented principle, where social structure consists of regularities in the patterns of relations among concrete entities.

  • Entities: individuals or any kind of organization.
  • Relations: specific contact, connection or tie between a pair of actors, or dyad (directed or nondirected).

Social Network Analysis¶

Look for the representation and measurement of these structural relations accurately, and to explain both why they occur and what are their consequences.

Explicitly assumes that actors participate in social systems connecting them to other actors, whose relations comprimse important influences on one another's behaviors.

Actors make decisions and act without regard to the other behavior of other actors?

Network research¶

  • Detect and represent structures accurately using relational data.
  • To explain the occurance of different structures and, at the actor level, to account for varionts in linkages to other actors.

Pattern relations underlying assumptions¶

  • Structural relations are often more important for understaging behaviors than attributes (specific time-place)
  • Social networks affect perceptiosn, beliefs, and actions through a variety of structural mechanisms that are socially constructed by relations among entities.
  • View as a dynamic process and not static processes.

By encompasing both structure and entities, it provides conceptual and methodological tools for linking changes in microlevel choices to macrolevel structural alterations.
